ce:section.ce:para:
As shown in Fig. 4
                        A, the fluorescence emission of GQDs and the absorption spectrum of NaTSPP had a remarkable spectral overlap, indicating the potential to produce efficient energy transfer from GQDs (as a donor) to NaTSPP (as an acceptor). Even though the spectral overlaps were minimal, a FRET mechanism could still be at play in the composites. As already stated, in addition to the π-π stacking coordination between GQDs and porphyrins, there was the possibility of electrostatic interactions due to the quaternized pyridinic nitrogen (N) of the porphyrins complexes which could lead to enhanced coordination to the GQDs. Replacing NaTSPP with FeTMPyP or TMOHPP, as shown in Fig. 4B and C, indicating the potential to produce efficient energy transfer from GQDs (as a donor) to FeTMPyP (as an acceptor) or TMOHPP (as an acceptor). There was an enhance in the fluorescence intensity of porphyrin when titrated with different concentrations of the GQDs (Fig. 5
                        ). This was owing to FRET between GQDs and porphyrins.
